      <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mr-2"><a href="/guides/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Guides</a></li>
      <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mr-2 text-gray-900 font-medium">CPF OA, SA, MA Explained</li>
    </ol>
  </nav>

  <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-4xl mx-auto text-gray-700">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-black text-gray-900 mb-6">CPF OA, SA, MA Explained: How Your Contributions Are Split</h1>

    <p>
      Every month, your CPF contributions and your employer's contributions are deposited into your Central Provident Fund accounts. But unlike a simple savings account, CPF splits your money across three distinct accounts, each with its own purpose, interest rate, and withdrawal rules. Understanding how the Ordinary Account (OA), Special Account (SA), and MediSave Account (MA) work is fundamental to making the most of your CPF savings - whether for buying a home, planning for retirement, or managing healthcare costs.
    </p>

    <p>
      This guide explains the purpose of each account, how contributions are allocated by age group, the interest rates each account earns, and the practical implications for your financial planning in Singapore.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">The Three CPF Accounts</h2>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Ordinary Account (OA)</h3>
    <p>
      The Ordinary Account is the most versatile of the three CPF accounts. OA funds can be used for:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Housing:</strong> Purchasing HDB flats or private property, paying monthly mortgage instalments, and covering stamp duties and legal fees.</li>
      <li><strong>Education:</strong> Paying for approved full-time courses at local universities and polytechnics for yourself or your children.</li>
      <li><strong>Insurance:</strong> Paying premiums for CPF-approved insurance schemes, including the Home Protection Scheme (HPS) and Dependants' Protection Scheme (DPS).</li>
      <li><strong>Investment:</strong> Investing in approved financial products such as unit trusts, stocks, bonds, and gold through the CPF Investment Scheme (CPFIS).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The OA earns a guaranteed minimum interest rate of <strong>2.5% per annum</strong>. While this is modest compared to some investment returns, it is risk-free and guaranteed by the Singapore government. The OA typically receives the largest share of CPF contributions for younger workers, reflecting the priority of housing purchases during the early and mid-career years.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Special Account (SA)</h3>
    <p>
      The Special Account is specifically designed for retirement savings. SA funds are more restricted in their usage:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Retirement:</strong> SA funds form the basis of your retirement savings and are transferred to your Retirement Account (RA) when you turn 55.</li>
      <li><strong>Investment:</strong> You can invest SA funds through CPFIS, but only in a more limited range of products compared to OA - primarily unit trusts and investment-linked insurance products with higher risk ratings excluded.</li>
      <li><strong>CPF LIFE:</strong> SA savings contribute to your CPF LIFE annuity, which provides monthly payouts from age 65 for life.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The SA earns a guaranteed minimum interest rate of <strong>4% per annum</strong>, significantly higher than the OA rate. This higher rate makes the SA one of the best risk-free savings vehicles available in Singapore. Many financial planners recommend leaving SA funds untouched to benefit from the guaranteed compounding at 4%.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">MediSave Account (MA)</h3>
    <p>
      The MediSave Account is reserved for healthcare expenses. MA funds can be used for:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Hospitalisation:</strong> Paying for inpatient hospital bills at approved hospitals, including surgery, ward charges, and treatments.</li>
      <li><strong>Medical insurance:</strong> Paying premiums for MediShield Life (Singapore's basic health insurance plan), Integrated Shield Plans, and ElderShield/CareShield Life.</li>
      <li><strong>Outpatient treatments:</strong> Selected outpatient expenses including chronic disease management at CHAS clinics, vaccinations, and health screening.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Like the SA, the MA earns <strong>4% per annum</strong> in guaranteed interest. The MA has a ceiling (the Basic Healthcare Sum, currently $71,500 for 2026), and once this ceiling is reached, excess contributions are redirected to the OA and SA. This ceiling is designed to ensure that healthcare savings are adequate without excessive accumulation.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Allocation Ratios by Age Group</h2>

    <p>
      The percentage of total CPF contributions going to each account changes as you age. This reflects the evolving priorities at different life stages - younger workers need more in the OA for housing, while older workers need more in MA for healthcare.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age 35 and Below</h3>
    <p>
      For the total CPF contribution of 37% (employee 20% + employer 17%), the allocation is: <strong>OA 23% / SA 6% / MA 8%</strong> of wages. As a proportion of total CPF, this means approximately 62% goes to OA, 16% to SA, and 22% to MA. On a capped salary of $6,800, the monthly allocation is roughly $1,564 to OA, $408 to SA, and $544 to MA.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age Above 35 to 45</h3>
    <p>
      The allocation shifts slightly: <strong>OA 21% / SA 7% / MA 9%</strong> of wages. The SA and MA begin receiving larger shares as housing needs typically stabilise in the mid-30s to mid-40s, while retirement and healthcare planning become more important.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age Above 45 to 50</h3>
    <p>
      Allocation moves further: <strong>OA 19% / SA 8% / MA 10%</strong> of wages. By this age, many workers have completed or are close to completing their housing payments, and the priority shifts towards building SA and MA balances.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age Above 50 to 55</h3>
    <p>
      The allocation becomes: <strong>OA 15% / SA 11.5% / MA 10.5%</strong> of wages. The SA now receives a significantly larger share in preparation for the transfer to the Retirement Account at age 55.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age Above 55 to 60</h3>
    <p>
      After 55, the SA is closed and funds are transferred to the Retirement Account. The total contribution rate drops to 30%, allocated as: <strong>OA 11.5% / RA (via SA) 3.5% / MA 15%</strong> of wages. The MediSave allocation increases substantially to prepare for rising healthcare costs.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age Above 60 to 65</h3>
    <p>
      Total rate drops to 21%, with allocation: <strong>OA 3.5% / RA (via SA) 6.5% / MA 11%</strong>. The vast majority of contributions now go to retirement and healthcare accounts, with only a small fraction directed to the OA.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age Above 65 to 70</h3>
    <p>
      Total rate is 16%, allocated as: <strong>OA 1% / RA (via SA) 4% / MA 11%</strong>. Healthcare remains the dominant priority, with MediSave receiving the largest share.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900">Age Above 70</h3>
    <p>
      The lowest total rate of 12.5% applies, allocated: <strong>OA 1% / RA (via SA) 1% / MA 10.5%</strong>. At this age, nearly all CPF contributions flow into MediSave to cover the higher healthcare utilisation typical of older Singaporeans.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Interest Rates and Extra Interest</h2>

    <p>
      CPF accounts earn guaranteed interest rates that are among the most competitive risk-free rates available in Singapore:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>OA:</strong> 2.5% per annum (minimum). The actual rate is pegged to the 3-month average of major local banks' interest rates, with a floor of 2.5%.</li>
      <li><strong>SA and MA:</strong> 4% per annum (minimum). The actual rate is pegged to the 12-month average yield of the 10-year Singapore Government Securities plus 1%, with a floor of 4%.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      <strong>Extra interest:</strong> The first $60,000 of combined CPF balances (with up to $20,000 from OA) earns an additional 1% per annum. This extra interest is credited to the SA (or RA for members aged 55+). For members aged 55 and above, an additional 1% extra interest is earned on the first $30,000 of combined balances (with up to $20,000 from OA), bringing the total extra interest to 2% for the first $30,000 and 1% for the next $30,000.
    </p>

    <p>
      These extra interest provisions mean that the effective interest rate for smaller CPF balances can be significantly higher than the base rates. For a member with $60,000 in combined balances (with $20,000 in OA), the effective rate on the OA portion receiving extra interest is 3.5%, while the SA portion earns an effective 5%. For members aged 55+, rates can go even higher.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">The Retirement Account (RA)</h2>

    <p>
      When you turn 55, a Retirement Account is automatically created. Your SA savings are transferred to the RA, topped up by OA savings if needed, to meet the Full Retirement Sum (FRS). The FRS for members turning 55 in 2026 is set by the CPF Board and is adjusted periodically to account for inflation and rising costs of living. The RA earns up to 6% per annum (4% base + 2% extra interest on the first $30,000 for those 55 and above).
    </p>

    <p>
      Once the FRS is met, remaining OA and SA balances can be withdrawn in cash. The RA funds are used to provide monthly retirement payouts through CPF LIFE, which begins at age 65 and continues for life. The payout amount depends on your RA balance and the CPF LIFE plan you choose.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Practical Implications for Financial Planning</h2>

    <p>
      Understanding the OA/SA/MA allocation is crucial for several financial decisions:
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Housing:</strong> Your OA balance determines how much CPF you can use for property purchases. Young workers accumulate OA savings rapidly (23% of wages for those 35 and below), which is why many Singaporeans can afford their first HDB flat using primarily CPF. However, every dollar used from OA for housing is a dollar that does not earn the guaranteed 2.5% interest, so the decision to use CPF versus cash for housing has long-term implications.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Retirement adequacy:</strong> The SA's 4% guaranteed return makes it one of the most attractive savings vehicles in Singapore. Transferring OA funds to SA (a one-way, irreversible transfer) can significantly boost retirement savings through the power of compounding at a higher rate. However, funds transferred to SA can no longer be used for housing.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Healthcare preparedness:</strong> MediSave accumulation ensures you have funds for hospitalisation and insurance premiums. Monitoring your MA balance relative to the Basic Healthcare Sum helps you understand whether you are adequately covered. Once the MA reaches its ceiling, excess contributions flow to other accounts, which can be beneficial for housing or retirement savings.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Investment decisions:</strong> Both OA and SA funds can be invested through CPFIS, but the guaranteed returns (2.5% OA, 4% SA) set a high bar for investment performance. Historically, many CPFIS investors have underperformed the guaranteed rates after fees, leading financial advisers to recommend leaving funds in CPF rather than investing, particularly for the SA where the 4% guaranteed rate is difficult to beat risk-free.
    </p>

    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-4 not-prose">
      <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100 p-6 group">
        <summary class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          What are the CPF OA, SA, and MA accounts used for?
          <span class="text-primary text-xl group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform">+</span>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          The Ordinary Account (OA) can be used for housing, education, insurance, and investment. The Special Account (SA) is dedicated to retirement savings and limited retirement-related investments. The MediSave Account (MA) covers hospitalisation expenses, approved medical insurance premiums (including MediShield Life), and selected outpatient treatments. Each account has different withdrawal rules and interest rates.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100 p-6 group">
        <summary class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          How is the CPF contribution split across OA, SA, and MA?
          <span class="text-primary text-xl group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform">+</span>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          The split depends on your age. For members aged 35 and below, the allocation is 23% to OA, 6% to SA, and 8% to MA (out of the total 37% contribution rate). As you age, a larger share goes to MA and SA, while OA decreases. By age 70+, nearly all contributions go to MediSave. The exact ratios are set by the CPF Board and change at ages 35, 45, 50, 55, 60, 65, and 70.
        </p>
      </details>

      <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-100 p-6 group">
        <summary class="text-lg font-bold text-gray-900 cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
          What interest rates do CPF accounts earn?
          <span class="text-primary text-xl group-open:rotate-45 transition-transform">+</span>
        </summary>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
          The OA earns a minimum of 2.5% per annum, while SA and MA earn a minimum of 4% per annum. The first $60,000 of combined CPF balances (with up to $20,000 from OA) earns an extra 1% interest. Members aged 55 and above earn an additional 1% on the first $30,000, bringing the maximum extra interest to 2% for that tranche. These rates are guaranteed by the government.
        </p>
      </details>
    </div>

